17:46:08.672 [INFO]   tool='write' path='01_capture/influential/2026-03-23__hn-reports-of-codes-death.md' content='# Reports of code\'s death are greatly exaggerated (Steve Krouse, 2026-03-23)\n\n- **Captured:** 2026-03-23\n- **Source:** [https://stevekrouse.com/precision](https://stevekrouse.com/precision)\n- **HN context:** Front-page story on Hacker News\n\n## Summary\nSteve Krouse argues that while AI lets people turn English into running code, the feeling of precision from "vibe coding" fades once complexity and real-world edge cases appear. He contends the answer is not to abandon code, but to raise the level of abstraction. Code remains necessary: it\'s a tool for mastering complexity, not just software behavior.\n\nThe essay critiques claims that coding is obsolete (“coding is dead”). Krouse suggests stronger AIs will actually make better abstractions more valuable, since humans will use models for harder, more abstract problems, not just to ship more low-quality software.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n- AI makes basic coding faster but doesn’t remove the need for real abstraction.\n- The precision and mastery that code offers become more important as complexity grows.\n- Stronger models drive the need for better abstractions, not less code.\n\n' start_line=0 end_line=0
